CTRL_2="OS Service"
DESC_2=" "

CTRL_2_1="OS Service"
DESC_2_1=" "

CTRL_2_1_1="Remove NIS service"
DESC_2_1_1="The Network Information Service (NIS), formerly known as Yellow Pages, is a client-server directory service protocol used to distribute system configuration files. The NIS client (ypbind) was used to bind a machine to an NIS server and receive the distributed configuration files"

CTRL_2_1_2="Remove rsh serve"
DESC_2_1_2="The Berkeley rsh-server (rsh, rlogin, rexec) package contains legacy services that exchange credentials in clear-text"

CTRL_2_1_3="Remove rsh client"
DESC_2_1_3="The rshpackage contains the client commands for the rsh services"

CTRL_2_1_4="Remove talk server"
DESC_2_1_4="The talk software makes it possible for users to send and receive messages across systems through a terminal session. The talk client (allows initiate of talk sessions) is installed by default"

CTRL_2_1_5="Remove talk client"
DESC_2_1_5="The talksoftware makes it possible for users to send and receive messages across systems through a terminal session. The talkclient, which allows initialization of talk sessions, is installed by default"

CTRL_2_1_6="Remove telnet server"
DESC_2_1_6="The telnet-server package contains the telnet daemon, which accepts connections from users from other systems via the telnet protocol"

CTRL_2_1_7="Remove tftp server"
DESC_2_1_7="Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) is a simple file transfer protocol, typically used to automatically transfer configuration or boot machines from a boot server. The packages tftpd and atftp are both used to define and support a TFTP server"

CTRL_2_1_8="Remove xinetd"
DESC_2_1_8="The eXtended InterNET Daemon (xinetd) is an open source super daemon that replaced the original inetd daemon. The xinetddaemon listens for well known services and dispatches the appropriate daemon to properly respond to service requests"

CTRL_2_1_9="Disable chargen service"
DESC_2_1_9="chargen is a network service that responds with 0 to 512 ASCII characters for each connection it receives. This service is intended for debugging and testing purposes. It is recommended that this service be disabled"

CTRL_2_1_10="Disable daytime service"
DESC_2_1_10="daytime is a network service that responds with the server's current date and time. This service is intended for debugging and testing purposes. It is recommended that this service be disabled"

CTRL_2_1_11="Disable echo service"
DESC_2_1_11="echo is a network service that responds to clients with the data sent to it by the client. This service is intended for debugging and testing purposes. It is recommended that this service be disabled"

CTRL_2_1_12="Disable discard service"
DESC_2_1_12="discard is a network service that simply discards all data it receives. This service is intended for debugging and testing purposes. It is recommended that this service be disabled"

CTRL_2_1_13="Disable time service"
DESC_2_1_13="time is a network service that responds with the server's current date and time as a 32 bit integer. This service is intended for debugging and testing purposes. It is recommended that this service be disabled"

CTRL_3="Special Purpose Services"
DESC_3=" "

CTRL_3_1="Special Purpose Services"
DESC_3_1=" "

CTRL_3_1_1="Remove X Windows"
DESC_3_1_1="The X Window System provides a Graphical User Interface (GUI) where users can have multiple windows in which to run programs and various add on. The X Windows system is typically used on workstations where users login, but not on servers where users typically do not login"

CTRL_3_1_2="Disable Avahi Server"
DESC_3_1_2="Avahi is a free zeroconf implementation, including a system for multicast DNS/DNS-SD service discovery. Avahi allows programs to publish and discover services and hosts running on a local network with no specific configuration. For example, a user can plug a computer into a network and Avahi automatically finds printers to print to, files to look at and people to talk to, as well as network services running on the machine"

CTRL_3_1_3="Disable Print Server – CUPS"
DESC_3_1_3="The Common Unix Print System (CUPS) provides the ability to print to both local and network printers. A system running CUPS can also accept print jobs from remote systems and print them to local printers. It also provides a web based remote administration capability"

CTRL_3_1_4="Disable DHCP Server"
DESC_3_1_4="The Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is a service that allows machines to be dynamically assigned IP addresses"

CTRL_3_1_5="Configure Network Time Protocol (NTP)"
DESC_3_1_5="ntp is a daemon which implements the Network Time Protocol (NTP). It is designed to synchronize system clocks across a variety of systems and use a source that is highly accurate. More information on NTP can be found at http://www.ntp.org. ntp can be configured to be a client and/or a server. This recommendation only applies if ntp is in use on the system"

CTRL_3_1_6="Disabled LDAP"
DESC_3_1_6="The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) was introduced as a replacement for NIS/YP. It is a service that provides a method for looking up information from a central database"

CTRL_3_1_7="Disable NFS and RPC"
DESC_3_1_7="The Network File System (NFS) is one of the first and most widely distributed file systems in the UNIX environment. It provides the ability for systems to mount file systems of other servers through the network"

CTRL_3_1_8="Remove DNS Server"
DESC_3_1_8="The Domain Name System (DNS) is a hierarchical naming system that maps names to IP addresses for computers, services and other resources connected to a network"

CTRL_3_1_9="Remove FTP Server"
DESC_3_1_9="The File Transfer Protocol (FTP) provides networked computers with the ability to transfer files"

CTRL_3_1_10="Remove HTTP Server"
DESC_3_1_10="HTTP or web servers provide the ability to host web site content"

CTRL_3_1_11="Remove IMAP and POP server"
DESC_3_1_11="dovecot is an open source IMAP and POP3 server for Linux based systems"

CTRL_3_1_12="Remove Samba daemon"
DESC_3_1_12="The Samba daemon allows system administrators to configure their Linux systems to share file systems and directories with Windows desktops. Samba will advertise the file systems and directories via the Small Message Block (SMB) protocol. Windows desktop users will be able to mount these directories and file systems as letter drives on their systems"

CTRL_3_1_13="Remove HTTP Proxy Server"
DESC_3_1_13="Squid is a standard proxy server used in many distributions and environments"

CTRL_3_1_14="Remove SNMP Server"
DESC_3_1_14="The Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) server is used to listen for SNMP commands from an SNMP management system, execute the commands or collect the information and then send results back to the requesting system"

CTRL_3_1_15="Disabled rsync"
DESC_3_1_15="The rsync service can be used to synchronize files between systems over network links"

